               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. BALLANTINE</hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">conducted the Prosecution</hi>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18471122-name-1347" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18471122-name-1347" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18471122-name-1347" type="surname" value="HADLOW"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18471122-name-1347" type="given" value="SAMUEL JOSHEPH"></interp>SAMUEL JOSHEPH HADLOW.</persName>
                  </hi> I live at 15, Peckham-grove, Camberwell. I know Hyman—he is a dealer in marine stores, in Burdett-street, Camberwell—on the night of 5th Nov. I lost a copper, and on the 8th Nov. I went to Hyman's shop—I saw him, and gave him notice that my house had been broken on the night of 5th Nov. and a copper and the gate-bell, the keys of the doors, and the brass furniture from the doors had been taken—I asked</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="184711220224"></xptr>
               <p>him if anything had been brought to his shop—he said, "No"—I called to him again a few days after—he said to me, ""Have you heard anything of your copper?"—I said, "No," and said, "All these things, you know, make good for trade."</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18471122-name-1348" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18471122-name-1348" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18471122-name-1348" type="surname" value="QUINNEAR"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18471122-name-1348" type="given" value="GEORGE"></interp>GEORGE QUINNEAR</persName>
                  </hi> (<hi rend="italic">policeman, P</hi> 201.) I went to Hyman's house in consequence of what Walker said—I saw Hyman—I asked Walker in his presence if that was the man he sold a copper to on Saturday night, 6th Nov.—he said it was—Hyman denied it; he said, "I can assure you it in wrong, I did not buy a cooper of him"—Walker said, "I did sell the copper to you; you asked what I wanted; I said, 'Six shillings'; you weighted it, and gave us 6<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. 2<hi rend="italic">d</hi>. you asked where we lived, and we told you in John-street, Albany-road; you lit your pipe and was going with us, and we ran away"—the cooper has not been found.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18471122-name-1349" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18471122-name-1349" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18471122-name-1349" type="surname" value="RICE"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18471122-name-1349" type="given" value="ELIZABETH"></interp>ELIZABETH RICE.</persName>
                  </hi> I live in Southampton-street. I heard about a cooper, and on Saturday, 6th Nov., went to Hyman's house—his wife said he was not at home—I waited—he soon came home—I said to him, "I understand my boy brought a cooper here, and it is a very wrong thing to buy anything from children without their parents knowing it"—he came out from his shop—I said, "It is a very serious thing"—he said, "You keep your boy in your house, it will soon blow over if you do not let him go along with the rest."</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18471122-name-1350" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18471122-name-1350" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18471122-name-1350" type="surname" value="RICE"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18471122-name-1350" type="given" value="SAMUEL"></interp>SAMUEL RICE.</persName>
                  </hi> I live with my father, Thomas Rice, a blacksmith, in Southampton-street. I know Walker, Moore, and Morley—on Saturday evening I went with Moore and Walker to 3, Peckham-grove—they told me to get up to the window—I broke a square of glass and got in—there was a copper there—we took it away to a house up steps, and they would not buy it—we took it to Hyman, and he gave us 6<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. 2<hi rend="italic">d</hi>. for it, and <hi rend="italic">chucked</hi> it on the rag heap—he did not weigh it—my brother found it out, and told my mother, and I told my mother where I took it to.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. O'BRIEN.</hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Have you told us all that occurred? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> I took my mother where I took the copper—I and Walker went into Hyman's shop—we told him the copper was our father's, and we lived at 4, Bath-street.</p>
